# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: toroidal-inductors-and-transformers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Incorporated in Switzerland as **ABB Ltd**, and headquartered in Zurich, it is dual-listed on the Nasdaq Nordic exchange in Stockholm, Sweden, and the SIX Swiss Exchange in Zurich., in addition to OTC Markets Group's pink sheets in the United States.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] For 30 years, it has been a part of the Fortune Global 500.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Employees of ABB and its predecessor companies developed several technologies for generating, transmitting, and distributing electricity, as well as for enabling industrial automation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] One is the miniature circuit breaker, invented by Hugo Stotz, which protects against fires and is found in almost every home.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Predecessor ASEA was the first company to introduce a microprocessor into an industrial robot and it helped to develop the electric propulsion system "Azipod", which improved manoeuvrability by locating the propulsion system outside the hull.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB is made up of around 20 divisions structured into four business areas: Electrification, Motion, Process Automation and Robotics & Discrete Automation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Previously, it had a large power grids business, which was sold to Hitachi in 2020, as well as a turbocharging business, that was spun off in 2022.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Over the years, ABB made different acquisitions, with major ones in the 21st century including Baldor Electric, Thomas & Betts, and the GE Industrial Solutions division of General Electric.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The company's activities have been the subject of controversy on multiple occasions.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] US-based Combustion Engineering, acquired by ABB in 1990, exposed the company to asbestos-related litigation, which led to ABB’s first-ever loss in 2001.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] A final claims settlement was reached in 2006.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB has also been subject to three US Foreign Corrupt Practices Act bribery settlements in 2004, 2010, and 2022.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Additionally, in 2001, an ABB entity pleaded guilty to bid rigging.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During the 2010s, ABB largely focused its growth strategy on the robotics and industrial automation sectors.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Before the sale of its Power Grids division to Hitachi in 2020, ABB was Switzerland's largest industrial employer.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Allmänna Svenska Elektriska Aktiebolaget (ASEA, English translation: General Swedish Electrical Company Limited) was founded in 1883 in Västerås, Sweden by Ludvig Fredholm as manufacturer of electrical light and generators.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Brown, Boveri & Cie (BBC) was formed in 1891 in Baden near Zurich, Switzerland by Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown and Walter Boveri as a Swiss group of electrical engineering companies producing AC and DC motors, generators, steam turbines and transformers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] On 10 August 1987, ASEA and BBC announced they would merge to form ASEA Brown Boveri (ABB).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The new corporation would remain headquartered in both Zurich, Switzerland and Västerås, Sweden, with each parent company holding 50 percent.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The merger created a global industrial group with revenue of approximately $15 billion and 160,000 employees.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The merger also included the Finnish company Strömberg that had been purchased by ASEA the same year.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] When ABB began operations on 5 January 1988, its core businesses included power generation, transmission and distribution; electric transportation; and industrial automation and robotics.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In its first year, ABB undertook some 15 acquisitions, including the environmental control group Fläkt AB of Sweden, the contracting group Sadelmi/Cogepi of Italy, and the railway manufacturer Scandia-Randers A/S of Denmark.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1989, ABB purchased an additional 40 companies, including Westinghouse Electric's transmission and distribution assets, and announced an agreement to purchase the Stamford, Connecticut-based Combustion Engineering (C-E).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1990, ABB bought the robotics business of Cincinnati Milacron in the US.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The acquisition expanded ABB's automated spot-welding operations in the American automotive industry.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB's 1991 introduction of the IRB 6000 robot, demonstrated its increased capacity in this field.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The first modular robot, the IRB 6000, can be reconfigured to perform a variety of specific tasks.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The IRB 6000 was designed for spot-welding applications.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1990, ABB also expanded into Australia when it acquired Commonwealth Engineering's plant in Dandenong, Melbourne.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB continued to manufacture Comeng's B-class Melbourne tram at the plant.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] However, it did not continue manufacturing Comeng's Adelaide 3000 class railcar, which was manufactured by Clyde Engineering instead.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In the early 1990s, ABB started expanding in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] By the end of 1991, the company employed 10,000 people in the region.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The following year, that number doubled.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] A similar pattern played out in Asia, where the reform and opening up in China and the lifting of some economic sanctions, helped open the region to a new wave of outside investment and industrial growth.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In March 1992, ABB bought out the other shareholders of the formerly state owned BREL, making BREL a wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] It was subsumed into ABB Transportation in September 1992.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Amid the wider privatisation of British Rail during the 1990s, BREL was sold via a management buyout, with management and employees owning 20% and ABB and Trafalgar House 40% each.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] At the time of the management buyout, BREL's locations comprised Crewe, York, and two separate works in Derby; Derby Locomotive Works was closed by 1991.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] By 1994, ABB had 30,000 employees across Asia as well as 100 plants, engineering, service and marketing centers; numbers that would continue to grow.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Through the 1990s, ABB continued its strategy of targeted expansion in Eastern Europe, the Asia–Pacific region and the Americas.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1995, ABB agreed to merge its rail engineering unit with that of Daimler-Benz of Germany; the goal of this arrangement was to create the world's largest maker of locomotives and railway cars.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The new company, ABB Daimler-Benz Transportation (Adtranz), had an initial global market share of nearly 12 percent.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The merge took effect on 1 January 1996.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] A few months following the start of the 1997 Asian financial crisis, ABB announced plans to accelerate its expansion in Asia as well as to improve the productivity and profitability of its Western operations.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The company took an $850 million restructuring charge and shed 10,000 jobs as it scaled back some of its facilities in higher-cost countries and shifted resources towards emerging markets.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In June 1998, ABB announced that it would acquire Sweden-based Alfa Laval's automation unit, which at the time was one of Europe's top suppliers of process control systems and automation equipment.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1999, as a final step in the integration of the companies formerly known as ASEA and BBC, the directors unanimously approved a plan to create a unified, single class of shares in the group.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] That same year, ABB completed its purchase of Elsag Bailey Process Automation, a Netherlands-based maker of industrial control systems, for $2.1 billion.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The acquisition increased ABB's presence in the high-tech industrial robotics and factory control system sectors, reducing its reliance on traditional heavy engineering sectors such as power generation and transmission.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1999, the company sold its stake in the Adtranz train-building business to DaimlerChrysler.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Instead of building complete locomotives, ABB's transportation activities shifted increasingly toward traction motors and electric components.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] That same year, ABB and France-based Alstom announced the merger of their power generation businesses in a 50-50 joint company, ABB Alstom Power.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Separately, in December 1999, ABB agreed to sell its nuclear power business to British Nuclear Fuels of the United Kingdom.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2000, ABB divested its interests in ABB Alstom Power and sold its boiler and fossil-fuel operations (including Gas turbines) to Alstom.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In early 2002, ABB announced its first-ever annual loss, a $691 million net loss for 2001.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The loss was caused by ABB's decision to double its provisions for settlement costs from $470 million to $940 million in asbestos-related litigation against its American subsidiary Combustion Engineering.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The provisions were to cover claims linked to asbestos products sold by Combustion Engineering prior to its acquisition by ABB.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] At the same time, ABB's board announced it would seek the partial return of retirement pay from Goran Lindahl and Percy Barnevik, two former chief executive officers of the group.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Barnevik received some $89 million in pension benefits when he left ABB in 2001; Lindahl, who succeeded Barnevik as CEO, had received $50 million in pension benefits, which ABB's board called "excessive".
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2004, ABB sold its upstream oil and gas business, ABB Vetco Gray, to a consortium of private equity investors for an initial sum of $925 million.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB continued to play an active role in the oil and gas industry via its core automation and power technology businesses.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2005, ABB delisted its shares from the London Stock Exchange and Frankfurt Stock Exchange.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The following year, the company resolved its asbestos liabilities against its US subsidiaries, Combustion Engineering and ABB Lummus Global, Inc, for $1.43 billion.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] A three-part capital strengthening plan also aided in ABB's recovery.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In August 2007, ABB Lummus Global, ABB's downstream oil and gas business, was sold to CB&I for $950 million.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The sale led to ABB making an accelerated $204 million payment to the CE Asbestos PI Trust, a trust fund covering the asbestos liabilities of Combustion Engineering.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2008, ABB agreed to acquire Kuhlman Electric Corporation, a US-based maker of transformers for the industrial and electric utility sectors.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In November 2008, ABB acquired Ber-Mac Electrical and Instrumentation to expand its presence in Western Canada's oil and gas industries.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In September 2010, the company bought K-TEK, a manufacturer of level measurement instruments, for $50 million; it was incorporated into ABB's Measurement Products business unit within ABB's Process Automation division.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In July 2010, ABB in Cary, North Carolina received a $4.2 million grant from the US federal government to develop energy storing magnets.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] On 10 January 2011, ABB invested $10 million in ECOtality, a San Francisco-based developer of charging stations and power storage technologies, to enter North America's electric vehicle charging market.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] On 1 July of that year, the company announced its acquisition of Epyon B.V. of the Netherlands, a manufacturer of EV-charging infrastructure.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In early 2011, ABB acquired Baldor Electric for $4.2 billion in an all-cash transaction as part of ABB's strategy to increase its market share in the North American industrial motors segment.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] On 30 January 2012, the company announced the acquisition of Thomas & Betts, a North American specialist in low voltage products for industrial, construction and utility applications, in a $3.9 billion cash transaction.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] On 15 June 2012, ABB completed its acquisition of commercial and industrial wireless technology specialists Tropos.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In July 2013, ABB acquired Power-One in a $1 billion all-cash transaction to become the leading global manufacturer of solar inverters.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] That same year, Fastned selected ABB to supply more than 200 Terra fast-charging stations along highways in the Netherlands.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] On 6 July 2017, ABB announced it had completed its acquisition of Bernecker + Rainer Industrie-Elektronik (B&R), the largest independent provider of product and software-based open-architecture for industrial automation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During January 2018, ABB became the title partner of the ABB FIA Formula E Championship, the world's first fully electric international FIA motorsport series.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] On 30 June 2018, the company completed its acquisition of GE Industrial Solutions, General Electric's global electrification business.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] On 17 December 2018, ABB announced it had agreed to sell 80.1% of its Power Grids business to Hitachi; the former Power Grids division thus became a part of the Hitachi Group and was rebranded to Hitachi Energy.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During December 2022, it was confirmed that Hitachi had acquired the remaining 19.9% of the business.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In March 2020 ABB announced the intent to purchase Cylon Controls Ltd.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The acquisition enhanced ABB Electrification business' position in the commercial buildings segment.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Also in March 2020, ABB announced that it had agreed to sell its solar inverter business to Italian solar inverter manufacturer Fimer; the transaction includes all of ABB's manufacturing and R&D sites in Finland, Italy and India, along with 800 employees across 26 countries.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In November 2021, ABB completed the sale of its Mechanical Power Transmission business to RBC Bearings Inc. for $2.9 billion in cash.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The sale was part of ABB's broader strategy to streamline its business and reduce its range of activities.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In July 2022, the company announced the spinoff of its turbocharging business to shareholders.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The spinoff was completed in October 2022 when the business was listed on the SIX Swiss Exchange under the new name of Accelleron.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During December 2022, ABB opened a new 67,000 square metre robotics factory in Shanghai following a $150 million investment.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In May 2023, ABB announced that it had completed the acquisition of Siemens' low-voltage NEMA motors business, with manufacturing operations in Guadalajara, Mexico.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] At the time, the business employed around 600 people and generated revenues of approximately $63 million in 2021.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In June 2023, ABB agreed to acquire smart home automation provider Eve Systems.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In September 2023, ABB announced it would partner with the Well Done Foundation to monitor methane and greenhouse gas emissions from orphaned wells in the United States.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In January 2024, ABB acquired Real Tech, a prominent Canadian company specializing in innovative optical sensor technology for real-time water monitoring and testing.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] It also acquired two start-ups, Sevensense and the R&D engineering firm Meshmind, to expand its activities in AI and software.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] As of 2025, ABB planned to rebrand all of its residential electrical product lines acquired from GE with the ABB ReliaHome brand.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In October 2025, ABB agreed to sell its industrial robotics business to Softbank Group in a $5.4 billion deal—preempting plans to spin the division off as its own company in 2026.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The business has approximately 7,000 employees and with revenues in 2024 of $2.3 billion, it represented about 7 percent of ABB Group revenues.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In December 2025, it was announced ABB had completed its acquisition of Gamesa Electric's power electronics business in Spain from Siemens Gamesa, originally revealed in December 2024.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The acquired portfolio includes power conversion products such as wind converters for doubly-fed induction generators (DFIG), industrial battery energy storage systems (BESS), and utility-scale solar inverters.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1990, ABB launched Azipod, a family of electric propulsion systems that extends below the hulls of large ships, providing both thrust and steering functions.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Developed in cooperation with the Finnish shipbuilder Masa-Yards, Azipod has demonstrated the viability of hybrid-electric power in seagoing vessels, while also increasing maneuverability, fuel efficiency and space efficiency.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1998, ABB launched the FlexPicker, a robot using a three-armed delta design uniquely suited to the picking and packing industry.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2000, ABB brought to market the world's first commercial high-voltage shore-to-ship electric power, at the Swedish port of Gothenburg.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Supplying electricity to berthed ships from the shore enables vessels to shut down their engines while in port, significantly reducing noise, vibrations and carbon emissions.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2004, ABB launched its Extended Automation System 800xA, an industrial system for the process industries.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Today, the company is the global market leader in distributed control systems.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In May 2013, ABB Sécheron SA joined with several groups in Geneva TOSA (Trolleybus Optimisation Système Alimentation, or in English, Trolleybus Power System Optimization) in a one-year demonstration of a trolleybus route using a novel charging system.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Rather than overhead wires, charging is accomplished by fixed overhead devices located at stops along the route and at the terminus.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Jean-Luc Favre, head of Rail ISI, discussed the promising role of improved electric transport technology in ABB.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2014, ABB unveiled YuMi, a collaborative industrial dual-arm assembly robot that permits people and machines to work side by side, unlocking new potential for automation in a range of industries.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2018, ABB unveiled the Terra High Power charger for electric vehicles, capable of delivering enough to charge in eight minutes to enable an electric car to travel 200 kilometers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2025, ABB Building Automation and Controls, a division of Electrification Smart Buildings, introduced ABB Ability BuildingPro, for smart building automation and management.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] It is designed as a fully integrated cloud-connected platform, and unifies HVAC, lighting, energy, and asset control under one interface.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] It is also said to have real-time visibility with AI and IoT-driven optimization, offering remote management across entire building portfolios.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] It has an open architecture and scalable edge-to-cloud design for interoperability and sustainability, enabling commercial buildings to achieve higher efficiency, lower operational costs, and improved occupant comfort.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB's Electrification business area offers products and services from substation to socket.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Customers include a wide range of industry and utility operations, plus commercial and residential buildings.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The business has strong exposure to rapidly growing segments, including renewables, data centers and smart buildings.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB Electrification offers technologies for low- and medium-voltage, including electric vehicle (EV) infrastructure, modular substations, distribution automation, power protection, wiring accessories, switchgear, enclosures, cabling, sensing and control.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The acquisition of GE Industrial Solutions, which was completed in June 2018, further strengthened ABB's #2 global position in electrification.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB's Motion business area provides a range of electrical motors, generators, drives and services, as well as integrated digital powertrain solutions.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Motion is the #1 player in the market globally.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In September 2023, it was announced ABB Motion had acquired a minority stake in the Burlington-headquartered wind turbine analytics software company, WindESCo.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB's Robotics & Discrete Automation business area combines machine and factory automation systems, mainly from B&R, which ABB acquired in 2017, with a comprehensive robotics concepts and applications suite.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB has installed over 300,000 robots globally.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The Robotics & Discrete Automation business has been positioned to capture the opportunities associated with the "factory of the future" by providing services for flexible manufacturing and smart machinery.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] According to a 2019 ABB press release, their automation business is #2 globally.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB is planning on expanding its innovation and production capacity by investing in a new robotics factory in Shanghai.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The Process Automation business area provides a range of automation, electrification and digital offerings for process, hybrid and maritime industries, including industry-specific integrated control and software, as well as measurement and analytics services.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The Power Grids business area offered components for the transmission and distribution of electricity, and incorporated ABB's manufacturing network for transformers, switchgear, circuit breakers, and associated high voltage equipment such as digital protective relays.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The division was subdivided into the four business units High Voltage Products, Transformers, Grid Automation and Grid Integration.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 2010, ABB's North American headquarters in Cary, North Carolina, announced a new partnership with Sensus of Raleigh, North Carolina, to develop technologies to work together on smart grids.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During 2014, ABB formed a joint venture with Hitachi to provide HVDC system solutions in Japan.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In December 2018, ABB and Hitachi announced that the latter would buy ABB's Power Grids division for roughly $6.4 billion.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Hitachi officially acquired 80.1% of the business in July 2020.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Initially known as *Hitachi ABB Power Grids*, the new Hitachi subsidiary was rebranded as Hitachi Energy in October 2021.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The transaction was one of Hitachi's biggest-ever deals, as it shifted focus to a higher-growth market for electricity networks.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Hitachi acquired the remainder of the company from ABB in 2022.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In July 2021, ABB confirmed the sale of its mechanical power transmission business, Dodge, to American company RBC Bearings Incorporated for $2.9bn.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] BREL was the first division of British Rail to be privatised as part of a phased plan initiated by the third Thatcher ministry.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB took over two rolling stock manufacturing facilities from BREL; the Derby Litchurch Lane Works and York Carriage Works.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Additionally, ABB took over Crewe Works in a purely maintenance capacity.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During September 1992, ABB Group purchased the stakes of the other members of the consortium to become the sole owner with the business rebranded ABB Transportation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The first trains produced at either facility under ABB ownership were for an order for 22 three-carriage Class 320 electric multiple units, built at ABB York for Glasgow's suburban railways in 1990.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] That same year, ABB York finished an order for five similar four-car Class 322 units for the new Stansted Express service.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Between 1990 and 1991, ABB York built 24 two-car Class 456 third rail trains for Network SouthEast services out of London Waterloo.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] A further order for 97 four-car Class 465 units was completed at ABB York for Network SouthEast services in and around Kent between 1991 and 1994.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Numerous diesel multiple units were also built at ABB York, including 76 Class 165 suburban units for Chiltern Main Line and Great Western Main Line commuter services between 1990 and 1992, followed by 21 Class 166 three-car express units for longer-distance services out of London Paddington.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1995, ABB Derby built 16 four-car Class 325 electric freight multiple units for the Royal Mail to replace their ageing fleet of parcels carriages.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During the mid-1990s, in a bid to expand their international portfolio, both the Derby and York plants completed a number of ABB Eurotram light rail vehicles for the Strasbourg tramway in France.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The last trains to roll off the production line at ABB York were an order for 41 four-carriage Class 365 electric multiple units for Connex South Eastern and West Anglia Great Northern services between 1994 and 1995.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Following the privatisation of British Rail, ABB encountered a decline in train orders, largely due to increased competition from competing manufacturers and no longer having a monopoly on rolling stock production in the British market.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During 1997, Adtranz unveiled the Class 168 train for Chiltern Railways.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The design of the Class 168 would subsequently be further developed into the Turbostar and Electrostar families of trains, which in turn became the most successful rolling stock design on post-privatisation British railways by number of units sold.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During 1999, ABB sold its 50% stake in Adtranz to Daimler for $472 million, thus exiting the rolling stock manufacturing sector.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Shortly thereafter, Daimler sold the Adtranz unit to Bombardier Transportation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Bailey, Bailey Controls developed the world's first steam boiler meter before becoming an industry leader in control and instrumentation of automated processes.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1989 the company merged with the Italian Elsag Group which also produced automation control and instrumentation devices.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Elsag Bailey Process Automation would be acquired by ABB in 1999.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In 1994 Fischer & Porter was acquired by Elsag Bailey Process Automation, which in turn was acquired by ABB in 1999.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Since August 2024, Morten Wierod has been ABB's CEO.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] During September 2013, Ulrich Spiesshofer was named ABB's CEO, succeeding Joe Hogan.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In August 2019, ABB announced industrial veteran Björn Rosengren would take over as CEO starting March 2020.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Rosengren was then serving as CEO of Swedish mining-equipment giant Sandvik.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In the meantime, ABB Chairman Peter Voser was appointed interim CEO on 17 April 2019, succeeding Ulrich Spiesshofer, who stepped down after five-and-a-half years.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Voser was elected chairman of the board of directors in April 2015 and succeeded Hubertus von Grünberg, who had been chairman since May 2007.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Jürgen Dormann was chairman from 2002 to 2007, and Percy Barnevik from 1999 to 2002.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The largest single stake in the firm is held by the Swedish investment company Investor AB, controlled by the Wallenberg family, which holds 12.9%.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Activist investor Cevian also holds a large stake in the company.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In December 2022, ABB was charged by the U.S.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] Securities and Exchange Commission for violations of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act in a bribery scheme in South Africa.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] It was ordered to pay a total of $460 million to U.S. authorities to settle criminal and civil charges.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB paid more than $37 million in bribes to a high-ranking Eskom official to influence contracts awarded by the state-owned electric utility company for work on the Kusile Power Station project between 2014 and 2017.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] The official had influence over the awarding of contracts for power projects in the country.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In exchange for the bribes, ABB secured a $160 million contract to provide services related to cabling and installation work at Eskom's Kusile Power Station, one of the largest coal-fired power plants in the world.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] In a parallel case, the United States Department of Justice fined ABB $315 million to settle criminal charges.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB had to pay $75 million in civil penalties to settle the SEC's charges.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] It was fined 4 million Francs by Swiss authorities.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/abb] ABB also agreed to repay $104 million to Eskom it was paid in connection with Kusile.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] An **amorphous metal transformer** (**AMT**) is a type of energy efficient transformer found on electric grids.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] The magnetic core of this transformer is made with a ferromagnetic amorphous metal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] The typical material (Metglas) is an alloy of iron with boron, silicon, and phosphorus in the form of thin (e.g.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] These materials have high magnetic susceptibility, very low coercivity and high electrical resistance.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] The high resistance and thin foils lead to low losses by eddy currents when subjected to alternating magnetic fields.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] On the downside amorphous alloys have a lower saturation induction and often a higher magnetostriction compared to conventional crystalline iron-silicon electrical steel.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] In a transformer the no-load loss is dominated by the core loss.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] With an amorphous core, this can be 70–80% lower than with traditional crystalline materials.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] The loss under heavy load is dominated by the resistance of the copper windings and thus called copper loss.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] Here the lower saturation magnetization of amorphous cores tends to result in a lower efficiency at full load.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] Using more copper and core material it is possible to compensate for this.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] So high efficiency AMTs can be more efficient at low and high load, though at a larger size.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] The more expensive amorphous core material, the more difficult handling and the need for more copper windings make an AMT more expensive than a traditional transformer.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] The main application of AMTs are the grid distribution transformers rated at about 50–1000 kVA.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] These transformers typically run 24 hours a day and at a low load factor (average load divided by nominal load).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] The no load loss of these transformers makes up a significant part of the loss of the whole distribution net.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] Amorphous iron is also used in specialized electric motors that operate at high frequencies of perhaps 350 Hz or more.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] More efficient transformers lead to a reduction of generation requirement and, when using electric power generated from fossil fuels, less CO2 emissions.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] This technology has been widely adopted by large developing countries such as China and India where labour cost is low.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] AMT are in fact more labour-intensive than conventional distribution transformers, a reason that explains a very low adoption in the comparable (by size) European market.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] These two countries can potentially save 25–30 TWh electricity annually, eliminate 6-8 GW generation investment, and reduce 20–30 million tons of CO2 emission by fully utilizing this technology.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] Kuwabara et al., Hitachi Review 60(2011) no.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] "SPC Note on T&D network loss reduction and energy saving plan" SPC Transportation and Energy Section, Document #123, 1997 (in Chinese).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] Naidu, "Amorphous Metal Transformers—New Technology Developments", Keynote Speech, CBIP-AlliedSignal Seminar (India), April 1999.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amorphous-metal-transformer] Li, Jerry (2011), Review and The Future of Amorphous Metal Transformers in Asia - a brief industry update, AEPN.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An **amplifier**, **electronic amplifier** or (informally) **amp** is an electronic device that can increase the magnitude of a signal (a time-varying voltage or current).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] It is a two-port electronic circuit that uses electric power from a power supply to increase the amplitude (magnitude of the voltage or current) of a signal applied to its input terminals, producing a proportionally greater amplitude signal at its output.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The amount of amplification provided by an amplifier is measured by its gain: the ratio of output voltage, current, or power to input.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An amplifier is defined as a circuit that has a power gain greater than one.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An amplifier can be either a separate piece of equipment or an electrical circuit contained within another device.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplification is fundamental to modern electronics, and amplifiers are widely used in almost all electronic equipment.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers can be categorized in different ways.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] One is by the frequency of the electronic signal being amplified.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] For example, audio amplifiers amplify signals of less than 20 kHz, radio frequency (RF) amplifiers amplify frequencies in the range between 20 kHz and 300 GHz, and servo amplifiers and instrumentation amplifiers may work with very low frequencies down to direct current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers can also be categorized by their physical placement in the signal chain; a preamplifier may precede other signal processing stages, for example, while a power amplifier is usually used after other amplifier stages to provide enough output power for the final use of the signal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The first practical electrical device which could amplify was the triode vacuum tube, invented in 1906 by Lee de Forest, which led to the first amplifiers around 1912.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The first practical prominent device that could amplify was the triode vacuum tube, invented in 1906 by Lee De Forest, which led to the first amplifiers around 1912.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Vacuum tubes were used in almost all amplifiers until the 1960s–1970s when transistors replaced them.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Today, most amplifiers use transistors, but vacuum tubes continue to be used in some applications.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The development of audio communication technology in form of the telephone, first patented in 1876, created the need to increase the amplitude of electrical signals to extend the transmission of signals over increasingly long distances.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In telegraphy, this problem had been solved with intermediate devices at stations that replenished the dissipated energy by operating a signal recorder and transmitter back-to-back, forming a relay, so that a local energy source at each intermediate station powered the next leg of transmission.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] For duplex transmission, i.e. sending and receiving in both directions, bi-directional relay repeaters were developed starting with the work of C.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Duplex transmission was essential for telephony and the problem was not satisfactorily solved until 1904, when H.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Shreeve of the American Telephone and Telegraph Company improved existing attempts at constructing a telephone repeater consisting of back-to-back carbon-granule transmitter and electrodynamic receiver pairs.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The Shreeve repeater was first tested on a line between Boston and Amesbury, MA, and more refined devices remained in service for some time.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] After the turn of the century it was found that negative resistance mercury lamps could amplify, and were also tried in repeaters, with little success.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The development of thermionic valves which began around 1902, provided an entirely electronic method of amplifying signals.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The first practical version of such devices was the Audion triode, invented in 1906 by Lee De Forest, which led to the first amplifiers around 1912.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Since the only previous device which was widely used to strengthen a signal was the relay used in telegraph systems, the amplifying vacuum tube was first called an *electron relay*.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The terms *amplifier* and *amplification*, derived from the Latin *amplificare*, (*to enlarge or expand*), were first used for this new capability around 1915 when triodes became widespread.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The amplifying vacuum tube revolutionized electrical technology.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] It made possible long-distance telephone lines, public address systems, radio broadcasting, talking motion pictures, practical audio recording, radar, television, and the first computers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] For 50 years virtually all consumer electronic devices used vacuum tubes.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Early tube amplifiers often had positive feedback (regeneration), which could increase gain but also make the amplifier unstable and prone to oscillation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Much of the mathematical theory of amplifiers was developed at Bell Telephone Laboratories during the 1920s to 1940s.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Distortion levels in early amplifiers were high, usually around 5%, until 1934, when Harold Black developed negative feedback; this allowed the distortion levels to be greatly reduced, at the cost of lower gain.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Other advances in the theory of amplification were made by Harry Nyquist and Hendrik Wade Bode.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The vacuum tube was virtually the only amplifying device, other than specialized power devices such as the magnetic amplifier and amplidyne, for 40 years.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Power control circuitry used magnetic amplifiers until the latter half of the twentieth century when power semiconductor devices became more economical, with higher operating speeds.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The old Shreeve electroacoustic carbon repeaters were used in adjustable amplifiers in telephone subscriber sets for the hearing impaired until the transistor provided smaller and higher quality amplifiers in the 1950s.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The first working transistor was a point-contact transistor invented by John Bardeen and Walter Brattain in 1947 at Bell Labs, where William Shockley later invented the bipolar junction transistor (BJT) in 1948.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] They were followed by the invention of the metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) by Mohamed M.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Atalla and Dawon Kahng at Bell Labs in 1959.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Due to MOSFET scaling, the ability to scale down to increasingly small sizes, the MOSFET has since become the most widely used amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The replacement of electron tubes with transistors during the 1960s and 1970s created a revolution in electronics, making possible a large class of portable electronic devices, such as the transistor radio developed in 1954.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Today, use of vacuum tubes is limited to some high power applications, such as radio transmitters, as well as some musical instrument and high-end audiophile amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Beginning in the 1970s, more and more transistors were connected on a single chip thereby creating higher scales of integration (such as small-scale, medium-scale and large-scale integration) in integrated circuits.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Many amplifiers commercially available today are based on integrated circuits.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] For special purposes, other active elements have been used.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] For example, in the early days of the satellite communication, parametric amplifiers were used.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The core circuit was a diode whose capacitance was changed by an RF signal created locally.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Under certain conditions, this RF signal provided energy that was modulated by the extremely weak satellite signal received at the earth station.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Advances in digital electronics since the late 20th century provided new alternatives to the conventional linear-gain amplifiers by using digital switching to vary the pulse-shape of fixed amplitude signals, resulting in devices such as the Class-D amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In principle, an amplifier is an electrical two-port network that produces a signal at the output port that is a replica of the signal applied to the input port, but increased in magnitude.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The input port can be idealized as either being a voltage input, which takes no current, with the output proportional to the voltage across the port; or a current input, with no voltage across it, in which the output is proportional to the current through the port.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The output port can be idealized as being either a dependent voltage source, with zero source resistance and its output voltage dependent on the input; or a dependent current source, with infinite source resistance and the output current dependent on the input.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Combinations of these choices lead to four types of ideal amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In real amplifiers the ideal impedances are not possible to achieve, but these ideal elements can be used to construct equivalent circuits of real amplifiers by adding impedances (resistance, capacitance and inductance) to the input and output.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] For any particular circuit, a small-signal analysis is often used to find the actual impedance.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] A small-signal AC test current *Ix* is applied to the input or output node, all external sources are set to AC zero, and the corresponding alternating voltage *Vx* across the test current source determines the impedance seen at that node as *R = Vx / Ix*.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers designed to attach to a transmission line at input and output, especially RF amplifiers, do not fit into this classification approach.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Rather than dealing with voltage or current individually, they ideally couple with an input or output impedance matched to the transmission line impedance, that is, match *ratios* of voltage to current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Many real RF amplifiers come close to this ideal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Although, for a given appropriate source and load impedance, RF amplifiers can be characterized as amplifying voltage or current, they fundamentally are amplifying power.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers are described according to the properties of their inputs, their outputs, and how they relate.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] All amplifiers have gain, a multiplication factor that relates the magnitude of some property of the output signal to a property of the input signal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The gain may be specified as the ratio of output voltage to input voltage (voltage gain), output power to input power (power gain), or some combination of current, voltage, and power.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In many cases the property of the output that varies is dependent on the same property of the input, making the gain unitless (though often expressed in decibels (dB)).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Most amplifiers are designed to be linear.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] That is, they provide constant gain for any normal input level and output signal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] If an amplifier's gain is not linear, the output signal can become distorted.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] There are, however, cases where variable gain is useful.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Certain signal processing applications use exponential gain amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers are usually designed to function well in a specific application, for example: radio and television transmitters and receivers, high-fidelity ("hi-fi") stereo equipment, microcomputers and other digital equipment, and guitar and other instrument amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Every amplifier includes at least one active device, such as a vacuum tube or transistor.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Negative feedback is a technique used in most modern amplifiers to increase bandwidth, reduce distortion, and control gain.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In a negative feedback amplifier part of the output is fed back and added to the input in the opposite phase, subtracting from the input.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The main effect is to reduce the overall gain of the system.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] However, any unwanted signals introduced by the amplifier, such as distortion are also fed back.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Since they are not part of the original input, they are added to the input in opposite phase, subtracting them from the input.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In this way, negative feedback also reduces nonlinearity, distortion and other errors introduced by the amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Large amounts of negative feedback can reduce errors to the point that the response of the amplifier itself becomes almost irrelevant as long as it has a large gain, and the output performance of the system (the "closed loop performance") is defined entirely by the components in the feedback loop.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This technique is used particularly with operational amplifiers (op-amps).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Non-feedback amplifiers can achieve only about 1% distortion for audio-frequency signals.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] With negative feedback, distortion can typically be reduced to 0.001%.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Noise, even crossover distortion, can be practically eliminated.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Negative feedback also compensates for changing temperatures, and degrading or nonlinear components in the gain stage, but any change or nonlinearity in the components in the feedback loop will affect the output.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Indeed, the ability of the feedback loop to define the output is used to make active filter circuits.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Another advantage of negative feedback is that it extends the bandwidth of the amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The concept of feedback is used in operational amplifiers to precisely define gain, bandwidth, and other parameters entirely based on the components in the feedback loop.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Negative feedback can be applied at each stage of an amplifier to stabilize the operating point of active devices against minor changes in power-supply voltage or device characteristics.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Some feedback, positive or negative, is unavoidable and often undesirable—introduced, for example, by parasitic elements, such as inherent capacitance between input and output of devices such as transistors, and capacitive coupling of external wiring.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Excessive frequency-dependent positive feedback can produce parasitic oscillation and turn an amplifier into an oscillator.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] All amplifiers include some form of active device: this is the device that does the actual amplification.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The active device can be a vacuum tube, discrete solid state component, such as a single transistor, or part of an integrated circuit, as in an op-amp.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Transistor amplifiers (or solid state amplifiers) are the most common type of amplifier in use today.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] A transistor is used as the active element.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The gain of the amplifier is determined by the properties of the transistor itself as well as the circuit it is contained within.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Common active devices in transistor amplifiers include bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) and metal oxide semiconductor field-effect transistors (MOSFETs).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Some common examples are audio amplifiers in a home stereo or public address system, RF high power generation for semiconductor equipment, to RF and microwave applications such as radio transmitters.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Transistor-based amplification can be realized using various configurations: for example a bipolar junction transistor can realize common base, common collector or common emitter amplification; a MOSFET can realize common gate, common source or common drain amplification.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Each configuration has different characteristics.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Vacuum-tube amplifiers (also known as tube amplifiers or valve amplifiers) use a vacuum tube as the active device.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] While semiconductor amplifiers have largely displaced valve amplifiers for low-power applications, valve amplifiers can be much more cost effective in high power applications such as radar, countermeasures equipment, and communications equipment.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Many microwave amplifiers are specially designed valve amplifiers, such as the klystron, gyrotron, traveling wave tube, and crossed-field amplifier, and these microwave valves provide much greater single-device power output at microwave frequencies than solid-state devices.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Vacuum tubes remain in use in some high end audio equipment, as well as in musical instrument amplifiers, due to a preference for "tube sound".
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Magnetic amplifiers are devices somewhat similar to a transformer where one winding is used to control the saturation of a magnetic core and hence alter the impedance of the other winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] They have largely fallen out of use due to development in semiconductor amplifiers but are still useful in HVDC control, and in nuclear power control circuitry due to not being affected by radioactivity.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Negative resistances can be used as amplifiers, such as the tunnel diode amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] A power amplifier is an amplifier designed primarily to increase the power available to a load.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In practice, amplifier power gain depends on the source and load impedances, as well as the inherent voltage and current gain.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] A radio frequency (RF) amplifier design typically optimizes impedances for power transfer, while audio and instrumentation amplifier designs normally optimize input and output impedance for least loading and highest signal integrity.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In general, the power amplifier is the last 'amplifier' or actual circuit in a signal chain (the output stage) and is the amplifier stage that requires attention to power efficiency.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Audio power amplifiers are typically used to drive loudspeakers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] They will often have two output channels and deliver equal power to each.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An RF power amplifier is found in radio transmitter final stages.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] A servo motor controller amplifies a control voltage to adjust the speed of a motor, or the position of a motorized system.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Power amplifier circuits (output stages) are classified as A, B, AB and C for analog designs—and class D and E for switching designs.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The power amplifier classes are based on the proportion of each input cycle (conduction angle) during which an amplifying device passes current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The image of the conduction angle derives from amplifying a sinusoidal signal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] If the device is always on, the conducting angle is 360°.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] If it is on for only half of each cycle, the angle is 180°.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The angle of flow is closely related to the amplifier power efficiency.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An operational amplifier is an amplifier circuit which typically has very high open loop gain and differential inputs.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Op amps have become very widely used as standardized "gain blocks" in circuits due to their versatility; their gain, bandwidth and other characteristics can be controlled by feedback through an external circuit.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Though the term today commonly applies to integrated circuits, the original operational amplifier design used valves, and later designs used discrete transistor circuits.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] A fully differential amplifier is similar to the operational amplifier, but also has differential outputs.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] These are usually constructed using BJTs or FETs.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] These use balanced transmission lines to separate individual single stage amplifiers, the outputs of which are summed by the same transmission line.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The transmission line is a balanced type with the input at one end and on one side only of the balanced transmission line and the output at the opposite end is also the opposite side of the balanced transmission line.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The gain of each stage adds linearly to the output rather than multiplies one on the other as in a cascade configuration.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This allows a higher bandwidth to be achieved than could otherwise be realised even with the same gain stage elements.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] These nonlinear amplifiers have much higher efficiencies than linear amps, and are used where the power saving justifies the extra complexity.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Class-D amplifiers are the main example of this type of amplification.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] A negative resistance amplifier is a type of regenerative amplifier that can use the feedback between the transistor's source and gate to transform a capacitive impedance on the transistor's source to a negative resistance on its gate.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Compared to other types of amplifiers, a negative resistance amplifier will require only a tiny amount of power to achieve very high gain, maintaining a good noise figure at the same time.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Video amplifiers are designed to process video signals and have varying bandwidths depending on whether the video signal is for SDTV, EDTV, HDTV 720p or 1080i/p etc.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The specification of the bandwidth itself depends on what kind of filter is used—and at which point (−1 dB or −3 dB for example) the bandwidth is measured.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Certain requirements for step response and overshoot are necessary for an acceptable TV image.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Traveling wave tube amplifiers (TWTAs) are used for high power amplification at low microwave frequencies.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] They typically can amplify across a broad spectrum of frequencies; however, they are usually not as tunable as klystrons.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Klystrons are specialized linear-beam vacuum-devices, designed to provide high power, widely tunable amplification of millimetre and sub-millimetre waves.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Klystrons are designed for large scale operations and despite having a narrower bandwidth than TWTAs, they have the advantage of coherently amplifying a reference signal so its output may be precisely controlled in amplitude, frequency and phase.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] New materials like gallium nitride (GaN) or GaN on silicon or on silicon carbide/SiC are emerging in HEMT transistors and applications where improved efficiency, wide bandwidth, operation roughly from few to few tens of GHz with output power of few watts to few hundred of watts are needed.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Depending on the amplifier specifications and size requirements microwave amplifiers can be realised as monolithically integrated, integrated as modules or based on discrete parts or any combination of those.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The maser is a non-electronic microwave amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Instrument amplifiers are a range of audio power amplifiers used to increase the sound level of musical instruments, for example guitars, during performances.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An amplifier's tone mainly comes from the order and amount in which it applies EQ and distortion.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] These amplifiers are used to amplify the voice of a person with watts, Examples are Megaphones, Microphones, personal amplifiers, etc.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] They are used for sporting events, schools, construction, and fire and safety.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] One set of classifications for amplifiers is based on which device terminal is common to both the input and the output circuit.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In the case of bipolar junction transistors, the three classes are common emitter, common base, and common collector.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] For field-effect transistors, the corresponding configurations are common source, common gate, and common drain; for vacuum tubes, common cathode, common grid, and common plate.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The common emitter (or common source, common cathode, etc.) is most often configured to provide amplification of a voltage applied between base and emitter, and the output signal taken between collector and emitter is inverted, relative to the input.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The common collector arrangement applies the input voltage between base and collector, and to take the output voltage between emitter and collector.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This causes negative feedback, and the output voltage tends to follow the input voltage.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This arrangement is also used as the input presents a high impedance and does not load the signal source, though the voltage amplification is less than one.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The common-collector circuit is, therefore, better known as an emitter follower, source follower, or cathode follower.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An amplifier whose output exhibits no feedback to its input side is described as 'unilateral'.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The input impedance of a unilateral amplifier is independent of load, and output impedance is independent of signal source impedance.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An amplifier that uses feedback to connect part of the output back to the input is a *bilateral* amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Bilateral amplifier input impedance depends on the load, and output impedance on the signal source impedance.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] All amplifiers are bilateral to some degree; however they may often be modeled as unilateral under operating conditions where feedback is small enough to neglect for most purposes, simplifying analysis (see the common base article for an example).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Another way to classify amplifiers is by the phase relationship of the input signal to the output signal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An 'inverting' amplifier produces an output 180 degrees out of phase with the input signal (that is, a polarity inversion or mirror image of the input as seen on an oscilloscope).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] A 'non-inverting' amplifier maintains the phase of the input signal waveforms.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An emitter follower is a type of non-inverting amplifier, indicating that the signal at the emitter of a transistor is following (that is, matching with unity gain but perhaps an offset) the input signal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Voltage follower is also non-inverting type of amplifier having unity gain.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This description can apply to a single stage of an amplifier, or to a complete amplifier system.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Other amplifiers may be classified by their function or output characteristics.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] These functional descriptions usually apply to complete amplifier systems or sub-systems and rarely to individual stages.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers are sometimes classified by the coupling method of the signal at the input, output, or between stages.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] By design these amplifiers cannot amplify DC signals as the capacitors block the DC component of the input signal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] RC-coupled amplifiers were used very often in circuits with vacuum tubes or discrete transistors.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In the days of the integrated circuit a few more transistors on a chip are much cheaper and smaller than a capacitor.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This kind of amplifier is most often used in selective radio-frequency circuits.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Quite often LC-coupled and transformer-coupled amplifiers cannot be distinguished as a transformer is some kind of inductor.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This class of amplifier was very uncommon in the vacuum tube days when the anode (output) voltage was at greater than several hundred volts and the grid (input) voltage at a few volts minus.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] So they were used only if the gain was specified down to DC (e.g., in an oscilloscope).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In the context of modern electronics developers are encouraged to use directly coupled amplifiers whenever possible.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In FET and CMOS technologies direct coupling is dominant since gates of MOSFETs theoretically pass no current through themselves.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Therefore, DC component of the input signals is automatically filtered.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Depending on the frequency range and other properties amplifiers are designed according to different principles.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers that operate down to DC are used only when direct-current response is needed.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers for direct current signals are vulnerable to minor variations in the properties of components with time.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Special methods, such as chopper stabilized amplifiers are used to prevent objectionable drift in the amplifier's properties for DC.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] "DC-blocking" capacitors can be added to remove DC and sub-sonic frequencies from audio amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers are designed according to different principles depending on their frequency range and other properties.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] As soon as any connection within the circuit gets longer than perhaps 1% of the wavelength of the highest specified frequency (e.g., at 100 MHz the wavelength is 3 m, so the critical connection length is approx.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] 3 cm) design properties radically change.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] For example, a specified length and width of a PCB trace can be used as a selective or impedance-matching entity.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Above a few hundred MHz, it gets difficult to use discrete elements, especially inductors.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In most cases, PCB traces of very closely defined shapes are used instead (stripline techniques).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The practical amplifier circuit shown above could be the basis for a moderate-power audio amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] It features a typical (though substantially simplified) design as found in modern amplifiers, with a class-AB push–pull output stage, and uses some overall negative feedback.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Bipolar transistors are shown, but this design would also be realizable with FETs or valves.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The input signal is coupled through capacitor C1 to the base of transistor Q1.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The capacitor allows the AC signal to pass, but blocks the DC bias voltage established by resistors R1 and R2 so that any preceding circuit is not affected by it.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Q1 and Q2 form a differential amplifier (an amplifier that multiplies the difference between two inputs by some constant), in an arrangement known as a long-tailed pair.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This arrangement is used to conveniently allow the use of negative feedback, which is fed from the output to Q2 via R7 and R8.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The negative feedback into the difference amplifier allows the amplifier to compare the input to the actual output.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The amplified signal from Q1 is directly fed to the second stage, Q3, which is a common emitter stage that provides further amplification of the signal and the DC bias for the output stages, Q4 and Q5.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] R6 provides the load for Q3 (a better design would probably use some form of active load here, such as a constant-current sink).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] So far, all of the amplifier is operating in class A.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The output pair are arranged in class-AB push–pull, also called a complementary pair.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] They provide the majority of the current amplification (while consuming low quiescent current) and directly drive the load, connected via DC-blocking capacitor C2.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The diodes D1 and D2 provide a small amount of constant voltage bias for the output pair, just biasing them into the conducting state so that crossover distortion is minimized.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] That is, the diodes push the output stage firmly into class-AB mode (assuming that the base-emitter drop of the output transistors is reduced by heat dissipation).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This design is simple, but a good basis for a practical design because it automatically stabilises its operating point, since feedback internally operates from DC up through the audio range and beyond.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Further circuit elements would probably be found in a real design that would roll-off the frequency response above the needed range to prevent the possibility of unwanted oscillation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] A common solution to help stabilise the output devices is to include some emitter resistors, typically one ohm or so.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Calculating the values of the circuit's resistors and capacitors is done based on the components employed and the intended use of the amp.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Any real amplifier is an imperfect realization of an ideal amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An important limitation of a real amplifier is that the output it generates is ultimately limited by the power available from the power supply.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] An amplifier saturates and clips the output if the input signal becomes too large for the amplifier to reproduce or exceeds operational limits for the device.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The power supply may influence the output, so must be considered in the design.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The power output from an amplifier cannot exceed its input power.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The amplifier circuit has an "open loop" performance.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This is described by various parameters (gain, slew rate, output impedance, distortion, bandwidth, signal-to-noise ratio, etc.).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Many modern amplifiers use negative feedback techniques to hold the gain at the desired value and reduce distortion.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Negative loop feedback has the intended effect of lowering the output impedance and thereby increasing electrical damping of loudspeaker motion at and near the resonance frequency of the speaker.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] When assessing rated amplifier power output, it is useful to consider the applied load, the signal type (e.g., speech or music), required power output duration (i.e., short-time or continuous), and required dynamic range (e.g., recorded or live audio).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] In high-powered audio applications that require long cables to the load (e.g., cinemas and shopping centres) it may be more efficient to connect to the load at line output voltage, with matching transformers at source and loads.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] This avoids long runs of heavy speaker cables.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] To prevent instability or overheating requires care to ensure solid state amplifiers are adequately loaded.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Most have a rated minimum load impedance.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] All amplifiers generate heat through electrical losses.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] The amplifier must dissipate this heat via convection or forced air cooling.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Heat can damage or reduce electronic component service life.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Designers and installers must also consider heating effects on adjacent equipment.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Different power supply types result in many different methods of bias.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Bias is a technique by which active devices are set to operate in a particular region, or by which the DC component of the output signal is set to the midpoint between the maximum voltages available from the power supply.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Most amplifiers use several devices at each stage; they are typically matched in specifications except for polarity.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Matched inverted polarity devices are called complementary pairs.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Class-A amplifiers generally use only one device, unless the power supply is set to provide both positive and negative voltages, in which case a dual device symmetrical design may be used.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Class-C amplifiers, by definition, use a single polarity supply.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Amplifiers often have multiple stages in cascade to increase gain.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] Each stage of these designs may be a different type of amp to suit the needs of that stage.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/amplifier] For instance, the first stage might be a class-A stage, feeding a class-AB push–pull second stage, which then drives a class-G final output stage, taking advantage of the strengths of each type, while minimizing their weaknesses.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In classical electromagnetism, **Ampère's circuital law**, often simply called **Ampère's law**, and sometimes **Oersted's law**, relates the circulation of a magnetic field around a closed loop to the electric current passing through that loop.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The law was inspired by Hans Christian Ørsted's 1820 discovery that an electric current generates a magnetic field.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] This finding prompted theoretical and experimental work by André-Marie Ampère and others, eventually leading to the formulation of the law in its modern form.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] James Clerk Maxwell published the law in 1855.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In 1865, he generalized the law to account for time-varying electric currents by introducing the displacement current term.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The resulting equation, often called the **Ampère–Maxwell law**, is one of Maxwell's equations that form the foundation of classical electromagnetism.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Until the early 19th century, electricity and magnetism were thought to be completely separate phenomena.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] This view changed in 1820 when Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted discovered that an electric current produces a magnetic effect.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] He observed that a compass needle placed near a current-carrying wire deflected so that it aligned perpendicular to the wire.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In a series of experiments, Ørsted demonstrated that the current could influence magnetic poles nearby, and that its effect extended outward from the wire.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] He also observed that this magnetic influence formed a vortex around the wire.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Ørsted's discovery sparked a great deal of research into the relation between electricity and magnetism.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] André-Marie Ampère investigated the magnetic force between two current-carrying wires, discovering Ampère's force law.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In the 1850s, Scottish mathematical physicist James Clerk Maxwell generalized these results and others into a single mathematical law.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The original form of Maxwell's circuital law, which he discussed in 1854 in correspondence with William Thomson (later ennobled as Lord Kelvin) and published in his 1855 paper "On Faraday's Lines of Force", was based on an analogy to hydrodynamics.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The original circuital law relates magnetic fields to electric currents that produce them and can be used to determine either the magnetic field associated with a given current, or the current associated with a given magnetic field.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] However, it applies only in magnetostatic situations, involving steady, continuous currents flowing in closed circuits.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In systems where electric fields vary with time, the original law (as given in this section) must be modified by adding a term known as Maxwell's correction (see below).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The integral form of the original circuital law is a line integral of the magnetic field around some closed curve C (arbitrary but must be closed).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The curve C in turn bounds both a surface S which the electric current passes through (again arbitrary but not closed—since no three-dimensional volume is enclosed by S), and encloses the current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The mathematical statement of the law is a relation between the circulation of the magnetic field around some path (line integral) due to the current which passes through that enclosed path (surface integral).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In terms of total current, (which is the sum of both free current and bound current) the line integral of the magnetic **B**-field (in teslas, T) around closed curve C is proportional to the total current *I*enc passing through a surface S (enclosed by C).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In terms of free current, the line integral of the magnetic **H**-field (in amperes per metre, A·m−1) around closed curve C equals the free current *I*f,enc through a surface S.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] There are a number of ambiguities in the above definitions that require clarification and a choice of convention.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Second, there are infinitely many possible surfaces S that have the curve C as their border.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] (Imagine a soap film on a wire loop, which can be deformed by blowing on the film).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Which of those surfaces is to be chosen?
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] If the loop does not lie in a single plane, for example, there is no one obvious choice.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The answer is that it does not matter: in the magnetostatic case, the current density is solenoidal (see next section), so the divergence theorem and continuity equation imply that the flux through any surface with boundary C, with the same sign convention, is the same.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In practice, one usually chooses the most convenient surface (with the given boundary) to integrate over.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The electric current that arises in the simplest textbook situations would be classified as "free current"—for example, the current that passes through a wire or battery.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In contrast, "bound current" arises in the context of bulk materials that can be magnetized and/or polarized.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] When a material is magnetized (for example, by placing it in an external magnetic field), the electrons remain bound to their respective atoms, but behave as if they were orbiting the nucleus in a particular direction, creating a microscopic current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] When the currents from all these atoms are put together, they create the same effect as a macroscopic current, circulating perpetually around the magnetized object.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] This magnetization current **J**M is one contribution to "bound current".
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The other source of bound current is bound charge.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] When an electric field is applied, the positive and negative bound charges can separate over atomic distances in polarizable materials, and when the bound charges move, the polarization changes, creating another contribution to the "bound current", the polarization current **J**P.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] with **J**f the "free" or "conduction" current density.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] All current is fundamentally the same, microscopically.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Nevertheless, there are often practical reasons for wanting to treat bound current differently from free current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] For example, the bound current usually originates over atomic dimensions, and one may wish to take advantage of a simpler theory intended for larger dimensions.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The result is that the more microscopic Ampère's circuital law, expressed in terms of **B** and the microscopic current (which includes free, magnetization and polarization currents), is sometimes put into the equivalent form below in terms of **H** and the free current only.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] For a detailed definition of free current and bound current, and the proof that the two formulations are equivalent, see the "proof" section below.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] There are two important issues regarding the circuital law that require closer scrutiny.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] First, there is an issue regarding the continuity equation for electrical charge.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In vector calculus, the identity for the divergence of a curl states that the divergence of the curl of a vector field must always be zero.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Hence $\nabla \cdot (\nabla \times \mathbf {B} )=0\,,$ and so the original Ampère's circuital law implies that $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {J} =0\,,$ i.e. that the current density is solenoidal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] But in general, reality follows the continuity equation for electric charge: $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {J} =-{\frac {\partial \rho }{\partial t}}\,,$ which is nonzero for a time-varying charge density.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] An example occurs in a capacitor circuit where time-varying charge densities exist on the plates.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Second, there is an issue regarding the propagation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] To 'resolve' these situations (w/ eqn. above), the contribution of displacement current must be added to the current term in the circuital law.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] James Clerk Maxwell conceived of displacement current as a polarization current in the dielectric vortex sea, which he used to model the magnetic field hydrodynamically and mechanically.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] He added this displacement current to Ampère's circuital law at equation 112 in his 1861 paper "On Physical Lines of Force".
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In free space, the displacement current is related to the time rate of change of electric field.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In a dielectric the above contribution to displacement current is present too, but a major contribution to the displacement current is related to the polarization of the individual molecules of the dielectric material.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Even though charges cannot flow freely in a dielectric, the charges in molecules can move a little under the influence of an electric field.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The positive and negative charges in molecules separate under the applied field, causing an increase in the state of polarization, expressed as the polarization density **P**.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] A changing state of polarization is equivalent to a current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The first term on the right hand side is present everywhere, even in a vacuum.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] It doesn't involve any actual movement of charge, but it nevertheless has an associated magnetic field, as if it were an actual current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Some authors apply the name *displacement current* to only this contribution.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] The second term on the right hand side is the displacement current as originally conceived by Maxwell, associated with the polarization of the individual molecules of the dielectric material.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Maxwell's original explanation for displacement current focused upon the situation that occurs in dielectric media.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In the modern post-aether era, the concept has been extended to apply to situations with no material media present, for example, to the vacuum between the plates of a charging vacuum capacitor.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] For greater discussion see Displacement current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Next, the circuital equation is extended by including the polarization current, thereby remedying the limited applicability of the original circuital law.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] In both forms **J** includes magnetization current density as well as conduction and polarization current densities.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Because ∇ ⋅ **D** = *ρ*, the charge continuity issue with Ampère's original formulation is no longer a problem.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] Because of the term in *ε*0⁠∂**E**/∂*t*⁠, wave propagation in free space now is possible.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] With the addition of the displacement current, Maxwell was able to hypothesize (correctly) that light was a form of electromagnetic wave.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/ampère-s-circuital-law] See electromagnetic wave equation for a discussion of this important discovery.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] An **audio power amplifier** (or **power amp**) amplifies low-power electronic audio signals, such as the signal from a radio receiver or an electric guitar pickup, to a level that is high enough for driving loudspeakers or headphones.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Audio power amplifiers are found in all manner of sound systems, including sound reinforcement, public address, home audio systems and musical instrument amplifiers like guitar amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] It is the final electronic stage in a typical audio playback chain before the signal is sent to the loudspeakers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The preceding stages in such a chain are low-power audio amplifiers, which perform tasks like pre-amplification of the signal, equalization, mixing different input signals.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The inputs can also be any number of audio sources like record players, CD players, digital audio players and cassette players.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Most audio power amplifiers require these low-level inputs, which are line level.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The audio amplifier was invented around 1912 by Lee de Forest.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] This was made possible by his invention of the first practical amplifying electrical component, the triode vacuum tube (or "valve" in British English) in 1907.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The triode was a three-terminal device with a control grid that can modulate the flow of electrons from the filament to the plate.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The triode vacuum amplifier was used to make the first AM radio.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Early audio power amplifiers were based on vacuum tubes and some of these achieved notably high audio quality (e.g., the Williamson amplifier of 1947–9).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Audio power amplifiers based on transistors became practical with the wide availability of inexpensive transistors in the late 1960s.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Since the 1970s, most modern audio amplifiers are based on solid-state transistors, especially the bipolar junction transistor (BJT) and the metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Transistor-based amplifiers are lighter in weight, more reliable and require less maintenance than tube amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The MOSFET was invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960. was adapted into a power MOSFET for audio by Jun-ichi Nishizawa at Tohoku University in 1974.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Power MOSFETs were soon manufactured by Yamaha for their hi-fi audio amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] JVC, Pioneer Corporation, Sony and Toshiba also began manufacturing amplifiers with power MOSFETs in 1974.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] In 1977, Hitachi introduced the LDMOS (lateral diffused MOS), a type of power MOSFET.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Hitachi was the only LDMOS manufacturer between 1977 and 1983, during which time LDMOS was used in audio power amplifiers from manufacturers such as HH Electronics (V-series) and Ashly Audio, and were used for music and public address systems.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Class-D amplifiers became successful in the mid-1980s when low-cost, fast-switching MOSFETs were made available.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Many transistor amps use MOSFET devices in their power sections, because their distortion curve is more tube-like.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Key design parameters for audio power amplifiers are frequency response, gain, noise, and distortion.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] These are interdependent; increasing gain often leads to undesirable increases in noise and distortion.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] While negative feedback actually reduces the gain, it also reduces distortion.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Most audio amplifiers are linear amplifiers operating in class AB.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Until the 1970s, most amplifiers used vacuum tubes.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] During the 1970s, tube amps were increasingly replaced with transistor-based amplifiers, which were lighter in weight, more reliable, and lower maintenance.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The class-D amplifier, which is much more efficient than class-AB amplifiers, is now widely used in consumer electronics audio products, bass amplifiers and sound reinforcement system gear, as class-D amplifiers are much lighter in weight and produce much less heat, but may introduce some noise.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Since modern digital devices, including CD and DVD players, radio receivers and tape decks already provide a "flat" signal at line level, the preamp is not needed other than as a volume control and source selector.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] One alternative to a separate preamp is to simply use passive volume and switching controls, sometimes integrated into a power amplifier to form an integrated amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The final stage of amplification, after preamplifiers, is the output stage, where the highest demands are placed on the transistors or tubes.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] For this reason, the design choices made around the output device (for single-ended output stages, such as in single-ended triode amplifiers) or devices (for push-pull output stages), such as the class of operation of the output devices is often taken as the description of the whole power amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] For example, a class-B amplifier will probably have just the high power output devices operating cut off for half of each cycle, while the other devices (such as differential amplifier, voltage amplifier and possibly even driver transistors) operate in class A.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] In a transformerless output stage, the devices are essentially in series with the power supply and output load (such as a loudspeaker), possibly via some large capacitor and/or small resistances.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] For some years following the introduction of solid-state amplifiers, their *perceived* sound did not have the excellent audio quality of the best valve audio amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] This led audiophiles to believe that tube sound had an intrinsic quality due to the vacuum tube technology itself.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] In 1970, Matti Otala published a paper on transient distortion.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Transient distortion later became known as transient intermodulation distortion (TIM).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Two years later, in a 1972 paper, Matti Otala reported that TIM was found to occur during very rapid increases in amplifier output voltage.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Papers also later revealed that TIM distortion was triggered not just by transients, but also by steady state sine tone measurements.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Further publications by Otala and other authors found the solution for TIM distortion, including increasing slew rate, decreasing preamp frequency bandwidth, and the insertion of a lag compensation circuit in the input stage of the amplifier in a way that makes the input stage more linear.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The next step in advanced design was the Baxandall Theorem, created by Peter Baxandall in England.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] This theorem introduced the concept of comparing the ratio between the input distortion and the output distortion of an amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] This new idea helped audio design engineers to better evaluate the distortion processes within an amplifier.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] By applying negative feedback, the Baxandall Effect can come into play, where, as the level of negative feedback is increased over a limited range, the 2nd harmonic distortion product is reduced as expected, but at the same time, the higher-order harmonic distortion products are increased instead.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] This has led to the myth that high levels of negative feedback are bad.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] However, as the level of negative feedback is increased beyond approximately 20 dB, all distortion products are further reduced, demonstrating that such higher levels of negative feedback have no downsides.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Important applications include public address systems, theatrical and concert sound reinforcement systems, and domestic systems such as a stereo or home-theatre system.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Instrument amplifiers including guitar amplifiers and electric keyboard amplifiers also use audio power amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] In some cases, the power amplifier for an instrument amplifier is integrated into a single amplifier "head" which contains a preamplifier, tone controls, and electronic effects.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] These components may be mounted in a wooden speaker cabinet to create a "combo amplifier".
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Musicians with unique performance needs and/or a need for very powerful amplification may create a custom setup with separate rackmount preamplifiers, equalizers, and a power amplifier mounted in a 19" road case.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Power amplifiers are available in standalone units, which are used by hi-fi audio enthusiasts and designers of public address systems (PA systems) and sound reinforcement systems.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] A hi-fi user of power amplifiers may have a stereo power amplifier to drive left and right speakers and a single-channel (mono) power amplifier to drive a subwoofer.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] The number of power amplifiers used in a sound reinforcement setting depends on the size of the venue.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] A small coffeehouse may have a single power amp driving two PA speakers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] A nightclub may have several power amps for the main speakers, one or more power amps for the monitor speakers (pointing towards the band) and an additional power amp for the subwoofer.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] A stadium concert may have a large number of power amps mounted in racks.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/audio-power-amplifier] Most consumer electronics sound products, such as TVs, boom boxes, home cinema sound systems, Casio and Yamaha electronic keyboards, "combo" guitar amps and car stereos have power amplifiers integrated inside the chassis of the main product.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] An **Austin ring transformer** is a special type of isolation transformer with low capacitance between the primary and secondary windings and high isolation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] It is named after its inventor, Arthur O.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] AM radio stations that broadcast in the medium frequency (MF) and low frequency (LF) bands typically use a type of antenna called a base-fed mast radiator.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] This is a tall radio mast in which the steel mast structure itself is energized and serves as the antenna.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] The mast is mounted on a ceramic insulator to isolate it from the ground and the feedline from the transmitter is bolted to it.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] Typically the mast will have a radio frequency AC potential of several thousand volts on it with respect to ground during operation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] Aviation regulations require that radio towers have aircraft warning lights along their length, so the tower will be visible to aircraft at night.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] The high voltage on the tower poses a problem with powering the lights.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] The power cable that runs down the tower and connects to the utility line is at the high voltage of the mast.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] Without protective equipment the RF current from the mast would flow down the cable to the power line ground, short-circuiting the mast.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] To prevent this, a protective isolator device is installed in the lighting power cable at the base of the mast which blocks the radio frequency power while allowing the 50/60 hertz AC mains power for the lights through.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] The Austin transformer is a specialized type of isolation transformer made specifically for this use, in which the primary and secondary windings of the transformer are separated by an air gap, wide enough so the high voltage on the antenna cannot jump across.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] It consists of a ring-shaped toroidal iron core with the primary winding wrapped around it, mounted on a bracket from the mast's concrete base, connected to the lighting power source.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] The secondary winding which provides power to the mast lights is a ring-shaped coil which circles the toroidal core through the center, like two links in a chain, with an air gap between the two.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] The magnetic field created by the primary winding induces current in the secondary winding without the necessity of a direct connection between them.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] The wide gap of several centimeters between the coils also ensures that there is minimal interwinding capacitance, to prevent RF voltage being induced in the supply wiring by capacitive coupling.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/austin-transformer] A spark gap is often located nearby with a gap smaller than the gap between the rings, to prevent damage to the transformer and transmitting equipment in the case of a lightning strike.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In electrical engineering, an **autotransformer** is an electrical transformer with only one winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The "auto" (Greek for "self") prefix refers to the single coil acting alone.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In an autotransformer, portions of the same winding act as both the primary winding and secondary winding sides of the transformer.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In contrast, an ordinary transformer has separate primary and secondary windings that are not connected by an electrically conductive path between them.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The autotransformer winding has at least three electrical connections to the winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Since part of the winding does "double duty", autotransformers have the advantages of often being smaller, lighter, and cheaper than typical dual-winding transformers, but the disadvantage of not providing electrical isolation between primary and secondary circuits.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Other advantages of autotransformers include lower leakage reactance, lower losses, lower excitation current, and increased VA rating for a given size and mass.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] An example of an application of an autotransformer is one style of traveler's voltage converter, that allows 230-volt devices to be used on 120-volt supply circuits, or the reverse.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] An autotransformer with multiple taps may be applied to adjust the voltage at the end of a long distribution circuit to correct for excess voltage drop; when automatically controlled, this is one example of a voltage regulator.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] An autotransformer has a single winding with two end terminals and one or more terminals at intermediate tap points.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] It is a transformer in which the primary and secondary coils have part of their turns in common.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The portion of the winding shared by both the primary and secondary is the common section.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The portion of the winding not shared by both the primary and secondary is the series section.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The primary voltage is applied across two of the terminals.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The secondary voltage is taken from two terminals, one terminal of which is usually in common with a primary voltage terminal.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Since the volts-per-turn is the same in both windings, each develops a voltage in proportion to its number of turns.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In an autotransformer, part of the output current flows directly from the input to the output (through the series section), and only part is transferred inductively (through the common section), allowing a smaller, lighter, cheaper core to be used as well as requiring only a single winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] One end of the winding is usually connected in common to both the voltage source and the electrical load.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The other end of the source and load are connected to taps along the winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Different taps on the winding correspond to different voltages, measured from the common end.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In a step-down transformer the source is usually connected across the entire winding while the load is connected by a tap across only a portion of the winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In a step-up transformer, conversely, the load is attached across the full winding while the source is connected to a tap across a portion of the winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] For a step-up transformer, the subscripts in the above equations are reversed where, in this situation, $N_{2}$ and $V_{2}$ are greater than $N_{1}$ and $V_{1}$ , respectively.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] As in a two-winding transformer, the ratio of secondary to primary voltages is equal to the ratio of the number of turns of the winding they connect to.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] For example, connecting the load between the middle of the winding and the common terminal end of the winding of the autotransformer will result in the output load voltage being 50% of the primary voltage.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Depending on the application, that portion of the winding used solely in the higher-voltage (lower current) portion may be wound with wire of a smaller gauge, though the entire winding is directly connected.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] If one of the center-taps is used for the ground, then the autotransformer can be used as a balun to convert a balanced line (connected to the two end taps) to an unbalanced line (the side with the ground).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] An autotransformer does not provide electrical isolation between its windings as an ordinary transformer does; if the neutral side of the input is not at ground voltage, the neutral side of the output will not be either.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] A failure of the isolation of the windings of an autotransformer can result in full input voltage applied to the output.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Also, a break in the part of the winding that is used as both primary and secondary will result in the transformer acting as an inductor in series with the load (which under light load conditions may result in nearly full input voltage being applied to the output).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] These are important safety considerations when deciding to use an autotransformer in a given application.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Because it requires both fewer windings and a smaller core, an autotransformer for power applications is typically lighter and less costly than a two-winding transformer, up to a voltage ratio of about 3:1; beyond that range, a two-winding transformer is usually more economical.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In three phase power transmission applications, autotransformers have the limitations of not suppressing harmonic currents and as acting as another source of ground fault currents.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] A large three-phase autotransformer may have a "buried" delta winding, not connected to the outside of the tank, to absorb some harmonic currents.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In practice, losses mean that both standard transformers and autotransformers are not perfectly reversible; one designed for stepping down a voltage will deliver slightly less voltage than required if it is used to step up.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The difference is usually slight enough to allow reversal where the actual voltage level is not critical.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Like multiple-winding transformers, autotransformers use time-varying magnetic fields to transfer power.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] They require alternating currents to operate properly and will not function on direct current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Because the primary and secondary windings are electrically connected, an autotransformer will allow current to flow between windings and therefore does not provide AC or DC isolation.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Autotransformers are frequently used in power applications to interconnect systems operating at different voltage classes, for example 132 kV to 66 kV for transmission.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Another application in industry is to adapt machinery built (for example) for 480 V supplies to operate on a 600 V supply.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] They are also often used for providing conversions between the two common domestic mains voltage bands in the world (100–130 V and 200–250 V).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The links between the UK 400 kV and 275 kV "Super Grid" networks are normally three phase autotransformers with taps at the common neutral end.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] On long rural power distribution lines, special autotransformers with automatic tap-changing equipment are inserted as voltage regulators, so that customers at the far end of the line receive the same average voltage as those closer to the source.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The variable ratio of the autotransformer compensates for the voltage drop along the line.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] A special form of auto transformer called a *zig zag* is used to provide grounding on three-phase systems that otherwise have no connection to ground.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] A zig-zag transformer provides a path for current that is common to all three phases (so-called zero sequence current).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In audio applications, tapped autotransformers are used to adapt speakers to constant-voltage audio distribution systems, and for impedance matching such as between a low-impedance microphone and a high-impedance amplifier input.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In railway applications, it is common to power the trains at 25 kV AC.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] To increase the distance between electricity Grid feeder points, they can be arranged to supply a split-phase 25–0–25 kV feed with the third wire (opposite phase) out of reach of the train's overhead collector pantograph.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The 0 V point of the supply is connected to the rail while one 25 kV point is connected to the overhead contact wire.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] At frequent (about 10 km) intervals, an autotransformer links the contact wire to rail and to the second (antiphase) supply conductor.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] This system increases usable transmission distance, reduces induced interference into external equipment and reduces cost.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] A variant is occasionally seen where the supply conductor is at a different voltage to the contact wire with the autotransformer ratio modified to suit.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Autotransformers can be used as a method of soft starting induction motors.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] One of the designs of such a starter is the Korndörfer autotransformer starter.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The autotransformer starter was invented in 1908, by Max Korndorfer of Berlin.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Patent office in May 1908 and was granted the patent US 1,096,922 in May 1914.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Max Korndorfer assigned his patent to the General Electric Company.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] An induction motor draws very high starting current during its acceleration to full rated speed, typically 6 to 10 times the full load current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Reduced starting current is desirable where the electrical grid is not of sufficient capacity, or where the driven load cannot withstand high starting torque.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] One basic method to reduce the starting current is with a reduced voltage autotransformer with taps at 50%, 65% and 80% of the applied line voltage; once the motor is started the autotransformer is switched out of circuit.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] By exposing part of the winding coils and making the secondary connection through a sliding brush, a continuously variable turns ratio can be obtained, allowing for very smooth control of output voltage.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The output voltage is not limited to the discrete voltages represented by actual number of turns.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The voltage can be smoothly varied between turns as the brush has a relatively high resistance (compared with a metal contact) and the actual output voltage is a function of the relative area of brush in contact with adjacent windings.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The relatively high resistance of the brush also prevents it from acting as a short circuited turn when it contacts two adjacent turns.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Typically the primary connection connects to only a part of the winding allowing the output voltage to be varied smoothly from zero to above the input voltage and thus allowing the device to be used for testing electrical equipment at the limits of its specified voltage range.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The output voltage adjustment can be manual or automatic.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The manual type is applicable only for relatively low voltage and is known as a variable AC transformer (often referred to by the trademark name Variac).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] These are often used in repair shops for testing devices under different voltages or to simulate abnormal line voltages.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The type with automatic voltage adjustment can be used as automatic voltage regulator, to maintain a steady voltage at the customers' service during a wide range of line and load conditions.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] Another application is a lighting dimmer that doesn't produce the EMI typical of most thyristor dimmers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] From 1934 to 2002, **Variac** was a U.S. trademark of General Radio for a variable autotransformer intended to conveniently vary the output voltage for a steady AC input voltage.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] In 2004, Instrument Service Equipment applied for and obtained the *Variac* trademark for the same type of product.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/autotransformer] The term *variac* has become a genericised trademark, being used to refer to a variable autotransformer.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Although closed-core inductors and transformers often use cores with a rectangular shape, the use of toroidal-shaped cores sometimes provides superior electrical performance.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The advantage of the toroidal shape is that, due to its symmetry, the amount of magnetic flux that escapes outside the core (leakage flux) can be made low, potentially making it more efficient and making it emit less electromagnetic interference (EMI).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Toroidal inductors and transformers are used in a wide range of electronic circuits: power supplies, inverters, and amplifiers, which in turn are used in the vast majority of electrical equipment: TVs, radios, computers, and audio power amplifiers.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] In general, toroidal inductors and transformers are more compact than other shaped cores, resulting in up to a 50% lighter weight design.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] This is especially the case for power devices.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Because the toroid is a closed-loop core, it has a higher inductance and Q factor than an inductor of the same mass with a straight core (solenoid coils).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] This is because most of the magnetic field is contained within the core.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] By comparison, with an inductor with a straight core, the magnetic field emerging from one end of the core has a long path through air to enter the other end.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Because the windings are relatively short and the magnetic field is closed, a toroidal transformer has higher efficiency, electrical performance, and reduces effects such as distortion and fringing.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Due to the symmetry of a toroid, little magnetic flux escapes from the core (leakage flux).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Thus, a toroidal inductor/transformer, couples less electromagnetic interference (EMI) to adjacent circuits and is often chosen for highly concentrated environments.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Manufacturers have adopted toroidal coils in recent years to comply with standards limiting the amount of electromagnetic field consumer electronics can produce.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] In some circumstances, the current in the winding of a toroidal inductor contributes only to the **B** field inside the windings.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] It does not contribute to the magnetic **B** field outside the windings.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] This is a consequence of symmetry and Ampère's circuital law.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The absence of circumferential current (the path of circumferential current is indicated by the red arrow in figure 3 of this section) and the axially symmetric layout of the conductors and magnetic materials are sufficient conditions for total internal confinement of the **B** field.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] (Some authors prefer to use the **H** field).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Because of the symmetry, the lines of B flux must form circles of constant intensity centered on the axis of symmetry.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The only lines of B flux that encircle any current are those that are inside the toroidal winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Therefore, from Ampere's circuital law, the intensity of the B field must be zero outside the windings.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Figure 3 of this section shows the most common toroidal winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] It fails both requirements for total B field confinement.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Looking out from the axis, sometimes the winding is on the inside of the core and sometimes on the outside of the core.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] It is not axially symmetric in the near region.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] However, at points a distance of several times the winding spacing, the toroid does look symmetric.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] There is still the problem of the circumferential current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] No matter how many times the winding encircles the core and no matter how thin the wire, this toroidal inductor will still include a one coil loop in the plane of the toroid.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] This winding will also produce and be susceptible to an **E** field in the plane of the inductor.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Figures 4-6 show different ways to neutralize the circumferential current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Figure 4 is the simplest and has the advantage that the return wire can be added after the inductor is bought or built.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] There will be a distribution of potential along the winding.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] This can lead to an **E**-Field in the plane of the toroid and also a susceptibility to an **E** field in the plane of the toroid, as shown in figure 7.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] This can be mitigated by using a return winding, as shown in Figure 8.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] With this winding, each place the winding crosses itself, the two parts will be at equal and opposite polarity, which substantially reduces the E field generated in the plane.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] See Feynman chapter 14 and 15 for a general discussion of magnetic vector potential.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] See Feynman page 15-11 for a diagram of the magnetic vector potential around a long thin solenoid which also exhibits total internal confinement of the **B** field, at least in the infinite limit.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The **A** field is accurate when using the assumption $bf{A}=0$ .
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Number 4 will be presumed for the rest of this section and may be referred to the "quasi-static condition".
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Although the axially symmetric toroidal inductor with no circumferential current totally confines the **B** field within the windings, the **A** field (magnetic vector potential) is not confined.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Arrow #1 in the picture depicts the vector potential on the axis of symmetry.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Radial current sections a and b are equal distances from the axis but pointed in opposite directions, so they cancel.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The situation for axial currents is different.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The axial current on the outside of the toroid is pointed down and the axial current on the inside of the toroid is pointed up.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Each axial current segment on the outside of the toroid can be matched with an equal but oppositely directed segment on the inside of the toroid.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The segments on the inside are closer than the segments on the outside to the axis, therefore there is a net upward component of the **A** field along the axis of symmetry.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Thus, a depiction of the **A** field around a loop of **B** flux (as would be produced in a toroidal inductor) is qualitatively the same as the **B** field around a loop of current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The figure to the left is an artist's depiction of the **A** field around a toroidal inductor.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The thicker lines indicate paths of higher average intensity (shorter paths have higher intensity so that the path integral is the same).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The lines are just drawn to look good and impart general look of the **A** field.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] is responsible for the undesirable electric field coupling between primary and secondary.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Transformer designers attempt to minimize the electric field coupling.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] will assumed to be zero unless otherwise specified.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The path integral of **E** along the secondary winding gives the secondary's induced EMF (Electro-Motive Force).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] which says the EMF is equal to the time rate of change of the B flux enclosed by the winding, which is the usual result.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] This figure shows the half section of a toroidal transformer.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Quasi-static conditions are assumed, so the phase of each field is the same everywhere.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The transformer, its windings and all things are distributed symmetrically about the axis of symmetry.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The windings are such that there is no circumferential current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The requirements are met for full internal confinement of the **B** field due to the primary current.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The core and primary winding are represented by the gray-brown torus.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The primary winding is not shown, but the current in the winding at the cross-section surface is shown as gold (or orange) ellipses.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The **B** field caused by the primary current is confined to the region enclosed by the primary winding (i.e. the core).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] Blue dots on the left-hand cross-section indicate that lines of **B** flux in the core come out of the left-hand cross-section.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] On the other cross-section, blue plus signs indicate that the **B** flux enters there.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The **E** field sourced from the primary currents is shown as green ellipses.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The secondary winding is shown as a brown line coming directly down the axis of symmetry.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The secondary is made of resistance wire, so there is no separate load.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The **E** field along the secondary causes current in the secondary (yellow arrows), which causes a **B** field around the secondary (shown as blue ellipses).
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] This **B** field fills space, including inside the transformer core, so in the end, there is a continuous non-zero **B** field from the primary to the secondary, if the secondary is not open-circuited.
[src:toroidal-inductors-and-transformers/toroidal-inductors-and-transformers] The cross product of the **E** field (sourced from primary currents) and the **B** field (sourced from the secondary currents) forms the Poynting vector, which points from the primary toward the secondary.
